ism in Canada -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJournalism in Crisis addresses the concerns of scholars, activists, and journalists committed to Canadian journalism as a democratic institution and as a set of democratic practices. The authors look within Canada and abroad for solutions for balancing the Canadian media ecology.Public policies have been central to the creation and shaping of Canada’s media system and, rather than wait for new technologies or economic models, the contributors offer concrete recommendations for how public policies can foster journalism that can support democratic life in twenty-first century Canada. Their work, which includes new theoretical perspectives and valuable discussions of journalism practices in public, private, and community media, should be read by professional and citizen journalists, academics, media activists, policy makers and media audiences concerned about the future of democratic journalism in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracyxCanada. 0aDemocracyzCanada. 0aDémocratiexCanada. 0aJournalismxCanada. 0aJournalismxPolitical aspectsxCanada. 0aJournalismxPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aJournalismxSocial aspectsxCanada. 0aJournalismxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aJournalismzCanada. 0aJournalismexAspect politiquexCanadaxCanada. 0aJournalismexAspect socialxCanada. 0aJournalismexCanada. 0aMass media policyxCanada. 0aMass media policyzCanada. 0aMass mediaxCanada. 0aMass mediazCanada. 0aMédiasxCanada. 0aMédiasxPolitique gouvernementalexCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aAlbinati, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAli, Christopher, econtribut